items.title: Person detained, home searched over Nancy Guthrie's disappearance
items.standfirst: The Pima County Sheriff's Department said deputies detained an individual during a traffic stop south of Tucson in Arizona and he is being spoken to regarding the missing 84-year-old.
items.content: Police are searching a home in Arizona and have detained a person for questioning over the disappearance of US TV host Savannah Guthrie's mother Nancy Guthrie.The Pima County Sheriff's Department said deputies detained an individual during a traffic stop south of Tucson in Arizona and he is being spoken to regarding the missing 84-year-old.The person was detained near the US-Mexico border in Rio Rico.EPSTEIN FILES: Trump named in the unredacted files 'more than a million times'READ MORE: Experts warn 'fun' new ChatGPT trend not as harmless as you may thinkA search warrant is currently being executed at a home in the same area.Rio Rico is located around 20 kilometres north of the US-Mexico border.No charges have been laid. The County Sheriff's Department said it would release more information as it became available.It remains unclear if the person in custody is the same person pictured in doorbell footage released earlier today. FBI director Kash Patel earlier told media that investigators were looking at multiple individuals as a "person of interest" in the case. He said the FBI's investigation has found there "might be person of interest in and around the area related to this event".Nancy, who has been missing for 10 days, was last seen at her home in Tucson on January 31.Her daughter, journalist and long-term co-anchor of the Today US television news program Savannah Guthrie, has issued repeated pleas for information and even appealed to the unknown kidnappers, offering to pay a ransom.The arrest comes after chilling CCTV footage of a man on the doorstep of her own was released by the FBI.Patel posted the images online early today, saying they had been recovered "from residual data located in backend systems". items.title: Police granted extra powers ahead of Israeli President's Melbourne visit
items.standfirst: Victoria Police has been granted special powers under the Terrorism Act ahead of Israeli President Isaac Herzog's visit to Melbourne tomorrow.
items.content: Victoria Police has been granted special powers to identify and search members of the public in certain areas ahead of Israeli President Isaac Herzog's visit to Melbourne tomorrow.Herzog will travel to Melbourne from Canberra tomorrow, after he met with mourners and survivors of the Bondi Terror Attack in Sydney earlier this week.Upwards of 5000 demonstrators are expected to gather at Flinders Street Station at 5pm tomorrow in opposition to the dignitary's arrival.READ MORE: Have Gen Z finally defied the smashed avo stereotype?Victoria Police Deputy Commissioner Regional Operations Bob Hill said the Supreme Court today granted police special powers under the Terrorism (Community Protection) Act as a "precautionary measure"."Victoria Police has been granted those powers that afford us, in specified areas, to seek the identities of individuals passing through that location, to search individuals, to search vehicles, and cordon-off a particular area," Hill said."It's specific to areas he will visit and it will not directly relate to or impact upon the lawful protest activity that may occur here in Melbourne tomorrow evening."The areas where the powers will apply will not be revealed in order to protect the president. Hill stressed the national terrorism threat level remained 'probable'' and said there were no active security threats against Herzog in Victoria."We want to be clear that there is no intelligence at this time to suggest that the event is the target of any specific threat," Hill said.READ MORE: Five-year-old girl dies after ATV rollover in Queensland"However, we are well prepared for both the visit and any protest activity this week, and have adequate police resources available to provide an agile response to any incidents."Around 5000 protesters took to the steps of Flinders Street Station on Monday."Monday's protest in Melbourne was largely peaceful and the majority of the crowd was well behaved. At this time, we are expecting Thursday's protests to be the same," Hill said."We respect the right of individuals to protest but only when it's done lawfully and peacefully."Again, our number one aim is to ensure the safety of all involved and we will be working with all parties to make sure that's the case."The president's four-day visit to Australia has been veiled in controversy with several protests shutting down cities across the country.Twenty-seven people were arrested, nine people have been charged, and five people were hospitalised after clashes between police and protesters in Sydney on Monday.NEVER MISS A STORY: Get your breaking news and exclusive stories first by following us across all platforms.Download the 9NEWS App here via Apple and Google PlayMake 9News your preferred source on Google by ticking this box hereSign up to our breaking newsletter here
